\f0\b\fs28 Release Notes.
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\
\'a5 The binaries are meant to be loaded on the CoCo using the 
\f2 LOADM
\f1  command. They are meant to be started using the 
\f2 EXEC
\f1  command. No need to specify the execution address.\
\
\'a5 The binaries produced by the compiler live at $4000 in RAM. The start up code inserted into your program sets the stack pointer at $6000, and switches to all-ram mode. This removes BASIC. When your program finishes, BASIC is brought back in and cold started.\
\
\'a5 Two libraries are being provided: libc and libRSDOS. The current libc is very minimal. Feel free to write more functions for it that are compatible with Standard C.  LibRSDOS contains functions specific to the Color Computer. Currently it is very small. Feel free to write more functions that can become part of libRSDOS.\
\
\'a5 These libraries live in the Library folder in the Programs folder. If you make changes to them you'll need to 
\f2 make
\f1  them, and then 
\f2 make install
\f1  them. You'll need to use 
\f2 sudo make install
\f1  on the Mac.\
